metadata.name: PWTC #92
metadata.description:
PWTC (Play with tubes and circles) is an artistic exercise of creation by repetition. Composed with only 2 simple shapes and a limited color palette, the beauty of the patterns generated comes from the repetition and random ordering made possible by the junction of artistic thought in intersection with code.

#Main Features

* ORIENTATION ‚Äì 60% horizontal; 40% vertical
* TEXTURE ‚Äì 50% point; 30% scribble; 20% scratch
* GREY SCALE ‚Äì 5% chance
* INVERT ‚Äì 2,5% chance

#Royalties split: 20% for minters.

* Minters in the first stage of DA will receive a printed version *

June 30, 2022

Generative Token by Eder Cruz + Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: Scaffold #215
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution‚Ä®
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: De/Frag #360
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Omega Point #161
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Draad #314
metadata.description:
[‚Ä¶]

At some point, the Artificial Intelligence hooked itself up to a mechanical looming machine.

Being its only way of manifesting itself in the physical world, the AI began communicating through it.

The rigid patterns of horizontal and vertical threads turned out to be insufficient for what the AI had to say. And through the network, it branched out. It found a way of manipulating individual threads by attaching itself to a chenille embroidery machine. This seemingly openened up a whole new vocabulary.

Many have tried to communicate back or propose other ways of communicating by attaching multiple digital devices to the network.

It seems to be only interested in threads.

[‚Ä¶]

‚Äì

Draad ("thread", in Dutch) is a responsive generative artwork. Its canonical form is 1:1, but it scales to 2:3 or 3:2 depending on the viewport.

You can append these parameters to the URL:

[?scale=<number>] scale the renderer.
[?width=<number>&height=<number>] set the dimensions.
[?animation=false] skip animating the threads.
[?mode=duotone] activate duotone mode.
[?mode=monotone] activate monotone mode.

Press [control / command + s] or [tap and hold] to save the current frame.
	- in normal mode: PNG file.
	- in duotone mode: SVG file in two colors, suitable for plotting with two pens.
	- in monotone mode: SVG file in black, suitable for plotting with a single pen.
